summary:
Two groups of armed assailants killed four policemen and injured another in Grozny, the capital of Chechnya in southwestern Russia, in a series of attacks on 17 and 18 December. One group of gunmen killed a policeman and took his weapon vehicle in the Oktiabrsky District on the evening of 17 December. The assailants then used the car to run over another policeman. Police cornered the first group in Lorsanov Street and killed three during a firefight and detained three of the assailants.
The second group attacked the apartment of another policeman and tied up members of his family, also on 17 December. When the policeman returned to his apartment the assailants stabbed him 17 times.
The same assailants targeted the vehicle of an employee of the Ministry of Internal Affairs in the village of Tashkala on 18 December. Police found the assailants in the village of Andreevskaya Dolina and killed four during a firefight and detained one of the assailants. Police said the two groups were in contact with each other.
Islamic State (IS) claimed responsibility for the attack in a statement posted online on 19 December.

summary:
A series of simultaneous remote-controlled IED explosions injured two people in Bannang Sata district, Yala Province, at around 2020hrs on 6 August. Unidentified assailants installed shrapnel bombs outside branches of the Government Savings Bank, the Bank for Agriculture and Agricultural Cooperatives, the Yala provincial land office, and the Bannang Sata Municipal office. Both venues were popular with foreigners and UN staff. Media reports indicate that the attackers shot indiscriminately into the crowds and set off explosives before making their way into the hotel.
Media outlets report that French and American security forces helped the domestic security forces to end the siege on the morning of 16 January. Towards the end of the siege, one attacker reportedly ran towards another hotel nearby called 'Le Yibi' before soldiers killed him. According to media reports, all attackers were 'young', and two of the attackers were female. Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (AQIM) has claimed responsibility for the attack.
